<p>
  Ask a room of people to describe the best toast they've ever heard, and very few will mention
  how polished the language was. They'll remember a moment: a specific story, a line that made
  everyone laugh at once, a detail that made it obvious the speaker truly knew the person they were
  toasting. Great toasts are built from a few consistent ingredients.
</p>

<h2>They're built around one story, not a summary</h2>
<p>
  The most common mistake is trying to summarize an entire friendship or relationship. The toasts
  people remember almost always zoom in on one specific moment — a trip, a conversation, a small
  gesture — and let that one story stand in for everything else you might have said.
</p>

<h2>They include a detail only the speaker could know</h2>
<p>
  A great toast makes the room feel like they're getting a glimpse behind the curtain — something
  only a close friend, sibling, or parent would know. That sense of insider knowledge is what makes
  a toast feel personal rather than interchangeable with any other wedding toast.
</p>

<h2>They have a clear point, not just warm feelings</h2>
<p>
  "I love you both so much" is true and nice, but it isn't a point — it's a feeling. The strongest
  toasts build toward something specific: a quality this person has that makes them a great partner,
  a piece of advice, a genuine observation about why this relationship works. Warmth matters, but a
  toast with a clear point tends to stick with people longer.
</p>
<blockquote>
  The best compliment we can receive is hearing, "That sounded exactly like me."
</blockquote>

<h2>They know when to stop</h2>
<p>
  A toast is not a speech — it's usually closer to one to two minutes, sometimes less. The best ones
  end while the room still wants more, on a genuine, well-timed final line, often followed directly
  by raising a glass. Overstaying a toast's welcome is one of the fastest ways to lose an otherwise
  great story.
</p>

<h2>They sound like the person giving them</h2>
<p>
  Above everything else, a toast that sounds like a template — however well-written — doesn't land
  the way a toast in the speaker's own voice does. If you're naturally understated, a toast full of
  big, sweeping statements will feel off, even if the sentiment is genuine. The goal isn't to sound
  impressive. It's to sound like you, saying something true.
</p>
